{
  "doc_id": "24740",
  "text": "From a gender perspective, our informants' experience of the father-child relationship reflected traditional masculinitynorms that normalize disregard of others' emotions [CITATION_1] . Rather than admitting their insecurities or perceived shortcomings and taking an intersubjective stance, men in our sample invoked their culturally sanctified prerogatives for dominance in the family by disregarding others' subjectivity, as has been described as typical masculine strategies in gender theories [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Additionally, the findings that the fathers acted dominantly in the family and felt increasingly excluded from the emotional domain mother and children shared, further illustrated what has been described in theories of gender and parenting [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Their lack of acknowledging mistakes and experiencing giving-in as losing face also fit with theories of male dominance as an established aspect of patriarchal societies [CITATION_6] .The findings from our study also reflect previous research on how traditional masculinity norms contribute to partner-abusive fathers' coercive tactics toward their children (Heward-Belle 2014; Katz 2016).",
